title: Could a human survive on Earth 200 million years ago? - Quora

response.answer_text: 200 million years ago marks the changeover from the Triassic Period to the Jurassic period. This occurs in the geologic record specifically because at that time, there was a Mass Extinction of life on Earth (called the Tr-J extinction). Almost 76% of all life on Earth went extinct. The land at the time represented Pangaea. The extinction event is believed to have occurred when the entire central portion of Pangaea (called the Central Atlantic Magmatic Province) began to rift and pull apart as Pangaea split, causing long-term massive volcanic eruptions which altered the climate so dramatically that plants and animals died off en mass.  If humans were dropped into this exact time-frame, what would they find? Studies have calculated that CO2 levels 200 million years ago from volcanism exceeded 2,500 ppm (vs. 420 ppm now). Atmospheric temperatures got hot enough to temperature-stress most plants, causing up to 80% of terrestrial plants to die off. Acid rain was severe across all of Pangaea, and oceans not only turned acidic but hot. Massive die-off of sea creatures occurred, including many fish. Certainly, shallow water fish died off first. There was enough oxygen to breathe, but a human being sent back in time would find a hothouse world filled with volcanic ash, extensive CO2 and Methane gases, plants and animals dying off and withering in brutal heat. The weather patterns in Pangaea at the time are unknown, but much of it is thought to have been arid, since it spanned both the equator and horse latitudes at 30 degrees north and south. Also note that at that time, there were no large mammals, so there would be no animal skins to use (unless you wore some reptile scales). No shoes, no protective pants or shirts to protect from a harsh sun …  Could a good survivalist from today survive then? Possibly! For how long? Not known. What his/her diet would be, what the climate would do to that person, whether they would find enough potable water in an acid-filled, arid climate while they panted and gasped for air in a sweltering CO2 laden volcanic world, what pathogens and animal predators they would encounter, what plants and animals could they eat when they knew nothing about them and most of them had died from the heat … are all good questions. Frankly, it would have sucked to be there … then!

Humans are apex predators. Megafauna extinction rates closely mirror human migration patterns where humans arrived as already skilled hunters and megafauna lacked time to develop defenses. This can be seen in Australia, Asia, Europe, North and South America and various isolated locations such as New Zealand and Madagascar but not in Africa where megafauna evolved alongside human beings. Indeed, stone tools and arrowheads unearthed at Cuddy Springs in south Australia were found to have traces of megafauna blood on their leading edges.These were in situ with a hearth that contained butchered and cooked megafauna bones clearly indicating the relationship between early humans and megafauna. Similar finds have also been made in North America, Siberia, and Asia, The mistake that some respondents have made in answering this question is that they are generalizing people into one category.Assuming perhaps that everyone shares the same skill set as themselves but that’s absolutely not the case. “The person wouldn’t know what to eat”.“The human beamed back in that time will not know anything about the fauna and flora back then.”“The person wouldn’t know which animal was safe to hunt and which one would fight back,” ect. A rugged, intelligent, well-read middle-aged survivalist who has spent his life in the bush (and there are MANY) is going to have VASTLY superior chances over a 16-year-old cheerleader from Brooklyn. Things were also not entirely alien.Water was still water and meat was still meat. Ferns for example existed 200 million years ago and have a fleshy heart and root system that are entirely edible. Fish, birds, turtles, and insects existed in the Jurassic and are almost all edible. Apex predators are usually obvious and predators broadly have various tells. K9 incisors, claws, usually forward-facing vision ect.We are also pre-programmed on a very primal level to recognize threat broadly. You can watch the animals and what they’re eating and you can test foods by rubbing it on a sensitive part of your skin, placing a small amount under your lip and introducing yourself to it in small doses or even smelling it to see if it smells like bitter almond which is a good sign its poisonous and cooked meat is almost exclusively safe to eat. You can boil your water, you can fortify a cave and create a safe space from which to plan your moves. So people vary in both survival skills and knowledge.A Zoologist will have a good understanding of the Fauna.So will a paleontologist.A botanist will have some understanding of the flora and of course, indigenous people such as Aboriginals and African Bushmen would also have a massive advantage. It would absolutely be possible for some humans to not only survive in the Jurassic but to prosper and those predators that you’re all so concerned about would ultimately have far more to fear from the introduction of humans into their habitat than we would of being introduced into it.

I disagree with Andrew McGregor's answer, so here is mine: Atmospheric oxygen has been at least 10% since the Cambrian. Compared to current levels of 21%, the Mesozoic 15% low is equivalent to the same O2 partial pressure experienced at around 3,000m altitude today, eminently survivable. Similarly, whilst far higher, CO2 levels were never sufficiently high to be asphyxiating, or even noticeably unpleasant due to tachypnea. Oxygen deprivation excluded, it takes around 10% concentration for fatal adverse effects, compared to 0.04% today and a maximum 0.2% (2,000ppm) in the Triassic. Despite higher temperatures, these were still seasonal, diurnal, latitude-dependent and localized, much as as today, and humans are actually better at thermo regulation than many mammals and reptiles. Temperate/polar areas would have been eminently surviveable, comfortable even. The main challenges would have been unfamiliar and inadequate foods (lack of angiosperms and grasses in particular) and challenging predators, but nothing human ingenuity could not overcome. Incidentally, your timing is out: 200Ma is already into the Jurassic. Give me a Barrett M82 and some decent survival equipment…  …and drop me somewhere nice at sea level, like Northern Greenland or Spitzbergen and I'd happily give it a go for a few months.  Most of the giant dinosaur mega-apex predators people are familiar with from the movies are actually of late Cretaceous age (T-rex, Raptors etc). Early (Hettangian) dinosaurs were of more manageable size.

There's a problem for our hypothetical time-traveller that nobody has mentioned yet, much to my surprise. Scurvy. Higher primates including humans cannot create vitamin C in their own bodies (unlike most animals). We have to get it from our food. Without a sufficient dietary intake of vitamin C a human will eventually die of scurvy. Unfortunately the best sources of vitamin C (fruit) hadn't evolved 200 million years ago. And while vitamin C is present in meat (eg liver) and shellfish, it's only present in small amounts and is destroyed by heat (ie cooking). Similarly it's present in leafy vegetables but is destroyed by heat. This wouldn't make it impossible for a human to survive 200 million years ago. But it would be tricky. A smart human who knows how to survive in the wild could hunt meat, make weapons and shelter, find and purify drinking water. They could probably clean and sterilise infections with fire, and maybe make alcohol (by fermenting starchy tubers? Had yeasts evolved by then? I'm not sure) to treat infections. There would be pathogens to deal with but most diseases would be adapted to infecting reptiles and dinosaurs, not mammals so diseases that affected humans might not be a serious problem. But this human would have to figure out which plants they could eat and develop a taste for wild salads (and hope they were high in vitamin C) or raw oysters in a hurry.

response.answer_text: The main problem with Earth 200 million years ago is the atmosphere itself. There was far less oxygen in the air than there is today and a lot more carbon dioxide. You would be choking for lack of oxygen and too much CO2. The Earth would be much hotter due to the CO2 and methane gases in the atmosphere trapping heat from the sun. Temperatures on land could easily reach 50-60°C (122-140°F) on land, and 40°C (104°F) at the sea-surface. Lethally Hot Temperatures During the Early Triassic Greenhouse Due to the above problems a lot of the plants and wildlife would have died off, leaving you with not a lot of food and there was often little water. In conclusion, it was dark due to all the green house gases, it was hot, there was little water, few animals and plants, and little oxygen for you to breathe and move about. This would not be a fun time to visit Earth as a human!  Look, a buffet of dinosaur bones! Cheers Andrew

Yes, assuming you didn’t just beam a clueless modern human back in time. If we assume a human that was born and grew up there, I don’t see why not. For most of our existence, humans have clustered on coasts and near bodies of water, because it offers the easiest access to food for hunter gatherers, and provides a generally milder climate. There wouldn’t be any grains, fruits, or familiar vegetables, but we can just look at existing human cultures for ways around that problem. Our diet would consist of fish, clams, prawns and other seafood, seaweed, edible ferns, and any edible seeds we could discover. Enterprising humans would eventually move inland, which is also totally possible, if a lot less comfortable. Likely they’d subsist on mushrooms, bugs, grubs, and meat, Instead of farming grain, I’d expect them to start breeding and cultivating fungi as a primary food source. Regarding predation by scary lizards, there aren’t really any serious concerns. Humans make fire, and it’s pretty safe to say that that would work just as well as a deterrent then as it has for us in our real prehistory.
